The paper deals with the problem of task-motion planning in autonomous driving, which involves both symbolic planning at the task level and trajectory planning at the motion level. This is a core problem in robotics, and is typically studied in the subfield of robotics (cs.RO). The paper also proposes an algorithm that uses machine learning techniques to optimize the trade-off between efficiency and safety, which suggests that it could be relevant to the subfields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the use of sensors and perception algorithms to detect obstacles and plan trajectories, which suggests that it could be relevant to the subfield of computer vision (cs.CV). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of urban driving, which involves navigating complex environments with many constraints, which suggests that it could be relevant to the subfield of control systems (cs.SY).
